 {"id":"bd-1d4","title":"[EPIC] Rich Rust Integration: Premium Human-Mode Console Output","description":"## Overview

This epic encompasses the complete integration of the rich_rust library throughout the Coding Agent Usage Tracker (caut) codebase to provide premium, stylish terminal output for human users while maintaining full compatibility with AI agent consumers.

## Background & Context

### The Problem
Currently, caut's terminal output is functional but visually basic. While the tool excels at fetching usage data from 16+ LLM providers, its human-facing output lacks the visual polish expected from modern CLI tools. Human users observing agent workflows deserve a premium experience.

### The Solution
Integrate rich_rust (a Rust port of Python's Rich library) to provide:
- Beautiful styled text with 24-bit color support
- Professional tables with auto-sizing columns
- Elegant panels and boxed content
- Informative progress indicators
- Consistent theming across all commands
- Graceful degradation for limited terminals

### Critical Constraint: Agent Safety
The PRIMARY users of caut are AI coding agents (Claude, Codex, Gemini, etc.) that parse the output programmatically. These agents MUST receive clean, parseable output without ANSI escape codes. All rich output features MUST be gated behind safety checks.

## Architecture Principles

### 1. Dual-Track Output (Human vs Robot)
- **Human Mode**: Rich, styled terminal output with colors, tables, panels
- **Robot Mode**: Clean JSON/Markdown output for agent consumption
- Mode detection is automatic based on environment and flags

### 2. Safety Gate Pattern
Every rich output feature MUST be wrapped in a safety check:
```rust
fn should_use_rich_output(args: &Args) -> bool {
    // Robot mode always gets plain output
    if args.robot_mode { return false; }
    // Respect NO_COLOR standard
    if std::env::var("NO_COLOR").is_ok() { return false; }
    // Respect CAUT_PLAIN override
    if std::env::var("CAUT_PLAIN").is_ok() { return false; }
    // Check if stdout is a real terminal
    std::io::stdout().is_terminal()
}
```

### 3. Graceful Degradation
Output must work well even when rich features are disabled:
- Colors auto-downgrade (24-bit → 256 → 16 → none)
- Box characters fallback to ASCII when needed
- Tables remain readable in plain mode

## Implementation Phases

### Phase 1: Foundation (Beads 1-4)
- Add rich_rust dependency
- Implement safety gate infrastructure
- Create theme system
- Build reusable component library

### Phase 2: Usage Command (Beads 5-8)
- Provider cards with styled output
- Summary tables with totals
- Error panels for failed fetches
- Progress indicators for fetching

### Phase 3: Supporting Commands (Beads 9-11)
- Cost command rich output
- Doctor command diagnostics display
- History command timeline visualization

### Phase 4: Error & Help System (Beads 12-14)
- Styled error messages
- Enhanced help output
- Version/branding display

### Phase 5: Testing & Polish (Beads 15-17)
- Comprehensive test coverage
- Performance validation
- Documentation updates

## Success Criteria
1. Human mode output is visually stunning
2. Robot mode output is 100% unchanged
3. No performance regression (< 5% overhead)
4. All existing tests pass
5. New tests cover all rich features
6. Theme system supports customization

## Dependencies
- rich_rust crate (from /dp/rich_rust or crates.io)
- Existing caut infrastructure (renderers, CLI args)

## Risks & Mitigations
| Risk | Mitigation |
|------|------------|
| Agents receive ANSI codes | Safety gate pattern, comprehensive tests |
| Performance degradation | Lazy initialization, benchmark suite |
| Terminal compatibility | Graceful degradation, ASCII fallback |
